{
  "version": "2.0.0",
  "cells": [
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "content": [
        "# Creating Custom 3D Objects in IDL",
        "",
        "IDL is a graphics language. One of the main things a graphic language does is display data. Towards this goal, it can be helpful to understand how to create and render 3D objects in IDL. This tutorial will go over a few ways of doing that."
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "content": [
        "### **Let's Start with Function Graphics**",
        "Function graphics are functions or procedures that we make for you. They are typically easier to use and more reliable than direct graphics. As such, **we recommend you use a function graphic whenever possible**. Here are a few common ones:"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "content": [
        "#### **Surface**",
        "",
        "The `surface()` function creates 3D surface plots from 2D data arrays. It takes a grid of Z values and renders them as an interactive 3D mesh. ",
        ">Good for visualizing mathematical functions, terrain data, or any z = f(x,y) relationship."
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "content": [
        "; Create sample data",
        "x = findgen(40)",
        "y = findgen(40)",
        "z = sin(dist(40)/2)",
        "",
        "; Create a 3D surface",
        "s = surface(z, x, y, title='Simple 3D Surface')"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [
        {
          "items": [
            {
              "mime": "idl/notebook-renderer",
              "content": "{\"type\":\"idlnotebookimage_png\",\"item\":{\"xsize\":640,\"ysize\":512,\"data\":\"\"}}"
            }
          ],
          "metadata": {
            "id": "not-saved"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "content": [
        "## Customizing",
        "This can be taken further with a plethora of easy keywords to modify its behavior so you can best fit your graphic to its purpose!"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "content": [
        "s = surface(z, x, y, $",
        "  color='blue', $",
        "  shading = 1, $",
        "  show_skirt = 1.0,$",
        "  /perspective, $",
        "  title='Styled 3D Surface', $",
        "  xtitle='X Axis', $",
        "  ytitle='Y Axis', $",
        "  ztitle='Z Axis')"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [
        {
          "items": [
            {
              "mime": "idl/notebook-renderer",
              "content": "{\"type\":\"idlnotebookimage_png\",\"item\":{\"xsize\":640,\"ysize\":512,\"data\":\"\"}}"
            }
          ],
          "metadata": {
            "id": "not-saved"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "content": [
        "#### **Volume**",
        "",
        "The `volume()` function is like `surface()`, but it takes a 3D array instead, allowing it to create 3D shapes!"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "content": [
        "; The size of the cube we want.",
        "n = 64L",
        "data = fltarr(n, n, n)",
        "",
        "; cube boundaries",
        "i0 = n/4L",
        "i1 = (3L * n)/4L",
        "data[i0:i1-1, i0:i1-1, i0:i1-1] = 1",
        "",
        "; Render. With keywords we can customize the appearance.",
        "v = volume(data, render_extents=0, $",
        "   hints=3, /auto_render, $",
        "   rgb_table0=70, axis_style=2, $",
        "   render_quality=2, background_color='gray', $",
        "   depth_cue=[0, 2], $",
        "   volume_location=[-10, -10, -10], $",
        "   volume_dimensions=[20.0, 20.0, 20.0])",
        ""
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [
        {
          "items": [
            {
              "mime": "idl/notebook-renderer",
              "content": "{\"type\":\"idlnotebookimage_png\",\"item\":{\"xsize\":640,\"ysize\":512,\"data\":\"\"}}"
            }
          ],
          "metadata": {
            "id": "not-saved"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "content": [
        "### **Object Graphics**",
        "IDL is also a fully functioning graphics language. You can work more directly with your renderer by using direct graphics. These commands are **more difficult** and **less guided** but give you finer control of your graphics. This tutorial will look into using Object Graphics for rendering polygons."
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "content": [
        "### IDLPolygons",
        "",
        "`IDLgrPolygon` is a Object graphics object that allows you to create custom 3D polygon meshes. Unlike function graphics like `surface()` or `volume()`, polygon objects give you complete control over:",
        "",
        "- **Vertices**: The 3D points that define your shape",
        "- **Connectivity**: How those points connect to form polygon faces",
        "- **Shading and styling**: Fill modes, colors, and lighting responses",
        "",
        "This approach is ideal when you:",
        "- want to create custom geometric shapes",
        "- import or generate geometry ",
        "- or want precise control over mesh appearance.",
        "",
        "The simplest IDLPolygon is the `orb()` object. Because you are using direct graphics, you need to handle the view and window yourself. `Xobjview` is the simplest way to do this. Using the two makes for a minimal example:"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "content": [
        "oModel = orb()",
        "xobjview, oModel"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "content": [
        "### More Powerful Polygons"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "content": [
        "If we want to make our own polygons, we need to construct them from the ground up. This mainly means we need to define a vertex array, a connectivity array, and then put those into a polygon object.",
        "",
        "Let's start with vertices:"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "content": [
        "verts = fltarr(3, 5)",
        "verts[*, 0] = [-0.5, -0.5, 0.0]  ; base corner 1",
        "verts[*, 1] = [ 0.5, -0.5, 0.0]  ; base corner 2",
        "verts[*, 2] = [ 0.5,  0.5, 0.0]  ; base corner 3",
        "verts[*, 3] = [-0.5,  0.5, 0.0]  ; base corner 4",
        "verts[*, 4] = [ 0.0,  0.0, 0.8]  ; apex"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "content": [
        "A vertex is a point that defines a corner of a polygon. Think of the pointy parts of a pyramid.",
        "",
        "However, the points of a polygon do not byt themselves make a polygon. To create the **faces** of the polygon, we need to define the **connectivity**—in other words, how these points connect with each other. Connectivity is in the format `[n_vertices, v1, v2, v3, v4, ...]`"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "content": [
        "; Define faces (base + 4 triangular sides)",
        "conn = [4, 0, 1, 2, 3, $        ; base (quad)",
        "        3, 0, 1, 4, $           ; side 1 (triangle)",
        "        3, 1, 2, 4, $           ; side 2",
        "        3, 2, 3, 4, $           ; side 3",
        "        3, 3, 0, 4]             ; side 4"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "content": [
        "It is important that we define connectivity in a counter-clockwise fashion so we adhere to the **right-hand rule** and our normals get generated properly.",
        "",
        "Now we have a polygon mesh. From here we need to apply this to a polygon object, and then we can display it!"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "content": [
        "oPoly = IDLgrPolygon(verts, polygons=conn, color=[200,100,50], shading=0, style=2)"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "content": [
        "Before we display it, we need to set up a model, a view, and a window. We are going to define the model manually as we want to add some lights and rotation. However, we are going to let view and window be taken care of by Xobjview."
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "content": [
        "; We are going to define simple versions for the sake of simplicity.",
        "",
        "oModel = IDLgrModel()",
        "oModel->add, oPoly",
        "",
        "; We add some lights and rotation so we can tell it's a pyramid.",
        "oModel->add, IDLgrLight(type=2, location=[5,5,10], intensity=0.8)",
        "oModel->add, IDLgrLight(type=2, location=[-5,-5,5], intensity=0.4)",
        "oModel->rotate, [1,0,0], -70 & oModel->rotate, [0,0,1], 30",
        "",
        "Xobjview, oModel"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "content": [
        "And boom! You have a rendered polygon! Pretty cool!",
        "",
        "### The Torus (doughnut)",
        "Let's do it again with a more complicated polygon:"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "content": [
        "",
        "",
        "; Define a function that creates a torus (donut) model",
        "function torus, n_u=n_u, n_v=n_v, major_r=major_r, minor_r=minor_r, color=color, rotation=rotation",
        "compile_opt idl2",
        "",
        "  ; Set defaults",
        "  if ~keyword_set(n_u) then n_u = 20      ; resolution around tube",
        "  if ~keyword_set(n_v) then n_v = 30      ; resolution around ring",
        "  if ~keyword_set(major_r) then major_r = 0.7  ; distance from center to tube",
        "  if ~keyword_set(minor_r) then minor_r = 0.3  ; tube thickness",
        "  if ~keyword_set(color) then color = [255, 140, 0]  ; orange",
        "  if ~keyword_set(rotation) then rotation = [-61.0, 0.0, 45.0]  ; default [x, y, z] rotation angles",
        "  ",
        "  n_verts = n_u * n_v",
        "  verts = fltarr(3, n_verts)",
        "  ",
        "  ; Build the vertices.",
        "  idx = 0",
        "  for i = 0, n_u - 1 do begin",
        "    u = i * 2.0 * !pi / n_u",
        "    for j = 0, n_v - 1 do begin",
        "      v = j * 2.0 * !pi / n_v",
        "      verts[0, idx] = (major_r + minor_r * cos(u)) * cos(v)  ; x",
        "      verts[1, idx] = (major_r + minor_r * cos(u)) * sin(v)  ; y",
        "      verts[2, idx] = minor_r * sin(u)                       ; z",
        "      idx++",
        "    endfor",
        "  endfor",
        "  ",
        "  ; Build connectivity array using quad strips.",
        "  ; It is important that the connectivity is set up in a counter-clockwise manner",
        "  ; so that normals point outward correctly.",
        "  ; This is consistent with OpenGL's default front-face definition.",
        "  conn = []",
        "  for i = 0, n_u - 1 do begin",
        "    i_next = (i + 1) mod n_u",
        "    for j = 0, n_v - 1 do begin",
        "      j_next = (j + 1) mod n_v",
        "      ",
        "      ; Define quad vertices in counter-clockwise order",
        "      v0 = i * n_v + j",
        "      v1 = i * n_v + j_next",
        "      v2 = i_next * n_v + j_next",
        "      v3 = i_next * n_v + j",
        "      ",
        "      conn = [conn, 4, v0, v1, v2, v3]",
        "    endfor",
        "  endfor",
        "  ",
        "  ; Create the IDLgrPolygon object (normals will be auto-computed).",
        "  oPolygon = IDLgrPolygon(verts, polygons=conn, $",
        "    color=color, $      ; color",
        "    shading=1, $        ; smooth shading",
        "    style=2)            ; filled",
        "  ",
        "  ; Create model and add polygon",
        "  oModel = IDLgrModel()",
        "  oModel->add, oPolygon",
        "",
        "  ; Rotate for better viewing.",
        "  oModel->rotate, [1, 0, 0], rotation[0]  ; tilt around x",
        "  oModel->rotate, [0, 1, 0], rotation[1]  ; tilt around y",
        "  oModel->rotate, [0, 0, 1], rotation[2]  ; rotate around z",
        "  ",
        "  return, oModel",
        "end",
        "",
        "",
        "; Create the torus model",
        "oModel = torus()",
        "",
        "; Add some lights",
        "oLight1 = IDLgrLight(type=2, location=[10, 10, 10], intensity=0.8)",
        "oLight2 = IDLgrLight(type=2, location=[-10, -10, 10], intensity=0.5)",
        "oLight3 = IDLgrLight(type=1, intensity=0.3)  ; ambient (non-directional)",
        "",
        "oModel->add, oLight1",
        "oModel->add, oLight2",
        "oModel->add, oLight3",
        "",
        "Xobjview, oModel",
        "",
        "; Note: This will open a separate window outside the notebook."
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "content": [
        "Because we made it a function that returns an oModel, it can be plugged in anywhere an oModel is accepted! Notably, **plot3d**:"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "content": [
        "seed = 2",
        "n = 8",
        "x = randomu(seed, n) * 5.0",
        "y = randomu(seed, n) * 5.0",
        "z = randomu(seed, n) * 3.0",
        "",
        "; Plot 3D data using custom torus objects as symbols",
        "p = plot3d(x, y, z, $",
        "  sym_object=torus(rotation=[-30, 100 , 0]), $",
        "  sym_size=2.5, $",
        "  linestyle='none', $",
        "  title='Plot3D with Custom Torus Symbols', $",
        "  xtitle='X Axis', ytitle='Y Axis', ztitle='Z Axis', $",
        "  xrange=[0, 5], yrange=[0, 5], zrange=[0, 3], $",
        "  aspect_ratio=1.0, aspect_z=0.6)"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [
        {
          "items": [
            {
              "mime": "idl/notebook-renderer",
              "content": "{\"type\":\"idlnotebookimage_png\",\"item\":{\"xsize\":640,\"ysize\":512,\"data\":\"\"}}"
            }
          ],
          "metadata": {
            "id": "not-saved"
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}